neral insights into espionage tactics and the motives of Americans who spied for Stalin, Spies resolves specific, long-seething controversies. The book confirms, among many other things, that Alger Hiss cooperated with Soviet intelligence over a long period of years, that journalist I. F. Stone worked on behalf of the KGB in the 1930s, and that Robert Oppenheimer was never recruited by Soviet intelligence. Spies also uncovers numerous American spies who were never even under suspicion and satisfyingly identifies the last unaccounted for American nuclear spies. Vassiliev tells the story of the notebooks and his own extraordinary life in a gripping introduction to the volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEspionage, SovietzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSpieszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aSpieszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aKlehr, Harvey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVassiliev, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVassiliev, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030012390640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015572340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300155723423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300155723/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY